.TH GTMPG "1"

.SH NAME
.B gtmpg.pl
- General Purpose Minecraft Tag Generator.

.SH SYNOPSIS
\&./gtmpg.pl [OPTION]

.SH DESCRIPTION
GTMPG, sometimes jokingly referred to as GregTech Masochist's Perl Generator is a
.B slof(5)
macro processor, originally developed for the purpose of automating converting minecraft tags saved in .slof format to a much more overcomplicated .json format.
However, after some small modifications it proved versitile for generating other json files too, as long as they could be mostly expressed as a simple array and a template file.

.RS 4
.B OPTIONS:

.B -t TEMPLATE_FILE
- use
.B TEMPLATE_FILE
as a template to replace. Defaults to tmp/tag.json.template if not specified.
.br
.B -e INPUT_EXTENSION
- search for files ending with
.B INPUT_EXTENSION.
.RE

.SH FILES OWNED BY GTMPG
.I tmp/cache
as directory tree structure.
.br
.I tmp/data/data/*.mctag
.br
.I tmp/data/*.cacsh

And others.

.SH HOW GTMPG WORKS
GTMPG begins by scanning a
.I tmp/cache
file, to discover the directory structure of ./tmp/ directory. It immediately prepares equivalent paths for ./generated/ directory as needed.
Specifically: it looks for files with the extensions specified by '-e' option, by default '.mctag'.

Next, GTMPG iterates through each slof file it found in the generated cache, and checks if the file is valid.
.RS 4

First it checks if a line is blank or a comment. If it is, it immediately skips it.

If it's not a comment, GTMPG checks if the entry is a valid minecraft ID or minecraft tag id, optionally with a word 'false' after whitespace. For example:

.B minecraft:apple false
.br
.B minecraft:stick

are valid GTMPG entries.
The first one will also add the
.I required: false
line to the generated tag. What this line does should be obvious to anyone familiar with datapacks.

If an entry is invalid, GTMPG will halt further generation, and will instead just print error messages.

.RE

If all entries are valid, GTMPG will write a generated file to a previously prepared path with a proper extension


.SH BUGS
GTMPG will default to .json output file extension, instead of taking an input from ARGV.
